"unless it is specified:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.10/site-packages/numpy/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.vectorize:126
msgid ""
"The `excluded` argument can be used to prevent vectorizing over certain "
"arguments.  This can be useful for array-like arguments of a fixed length "
"such as the coefficients for a polynomial as in `polyval`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.10/site-packages/numpy/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.vectorize:140
msgid "Positional arguments may also be excluded by specifying their position:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.10/site-packages/numpy/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.vectorize:146
msgid ""
"The `signature` argument allows for vectorizing functions that act on non-"
"scalar arrays of fixed length. For example, you can use it for a vectorized "
"calculation of Pearson correlation coefficient and its p-value:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.10/site-packages/numpy/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.vectorize:156
msgid "Or for a vectorized convolution:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.10/site-packages/numpy/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.vectorize:165
msgid ""
"Decorator syntax is supported.  The decorator can be called as a function to "
"provide keyword arguments. >>>@np.vectorize ...def identity(x): ...    "
"return x ... >>>identity([0, 1, 2]) array([0, 1, 2]) >>>@np."
"vectorize(otypes=[float]) ...def as_float(x): ...    return x ... "
">>>as_float([0, 1, 2]) array([0., 1., 2.])"
msgstr ""

